TY  - JOUR
T1  - Additive Information Processing and the Relationship Between Expectancy of Success and Motivational Force
AU  - Harrell, Adrian
AU  - Stahl, Michael
Y1  - 1986/06/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256197
DO  - 10.5465/256197
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 424
EP  - 433
VL  - 29
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this article the authors discuss research they have conducted that examines the relationship between expectancy of success and level of employee motivation. They discuss previous studies that have also examined this subject area noting that they have failed to recognize the relationship between expectancy of success and motivational force, which is their primary area of focus. They found that many individuals employ additive information processing when arriving at decisions that concern motivation and that this is in contrast with expectancy force models. They also found that increases in expectancy success resulted in declining marginal increases in motivation.
AB  - In this article the authors discuss research they have conducted that examines the relationship between expectancy of success and level of employee motivation. They discuss previous studies that have also examined this subject area noting that they have failed to recognize the relationship between expectancy of success and motivational force, which is their primary area of focus. They found that many individuals employ additive information processing when arriving at decisions that concern motivation and that this is in contrast with expectancy force models. They also found that increases in expectancy success resulted in declining marginal increases in motivation.
SN  - 0001-4273
